    <text>
        <body>
            <head>209. Memorandum From Ambassador-at-Large <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu"
                    >Nitze</persName> to Secretary of State <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                    >Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d209fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Lot 90D397, Ambassador <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>’s
                    Personal Files 1953, 1972–1989, September 1987. Secret; Sensitive. Printed from
                    an uninitialed copy.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1987-09-16"
                        >September 16, 1987</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">Arms Control</rs> Experts Meeting,
                    September 15</item>
            </list>
            <p>In our experts meeting last night, we addressed <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss>, <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>, and <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs>.
                We put off discussion of <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15"
                    >nuclear testing</rs> until today.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d209fn2">The
                    working group met from 10 p.m. to 12:30 a.m. the evening of September 15, and
                    from 4 to 7 p.m. on September 16. Memoranda of conversation are in the
                    Department of State, Executive Secretariat, S/S-IRM Records, Memoranda of
                    Conversations Pertaining to United States and <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                        >USSR</gloss> Relations, 1981–1990, Lot 93D188, Box 214, <persName
                        corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>-<persName
                        corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>—Wash—9/87.</note> The
                Soviets did not suggest experts meetings on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reczqT2YNc42Dimap">conventional forces</rs> or <rs
                    corresp="rectadvRz4QZmc1z7" type="topic">chemical weapons</rs>, but might in
                your meeting with <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName> this
                    morning.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d209fn3">See <ref target="#d210"
                        >Document 210</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>[Omitted here is a discussion of <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss>.]</p>
            <p>We made some headway on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>. <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> indicated the
                Soviets would be willing to express their offer to reduce their <rs
                    corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky" type="topic">SS–18</rs> force to 154 as a limit of
                1540 on <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> with a
                no-increase commitment. <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> also
                confirmed that their proposed 60% limit on any one leg of the <rs
                    corresp="rechRXFB0v2ifZPIR" type="compound-subject">triad</rs> did not alter
                their acceptance of the 6,000 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                    >warhead</rs> limit and of the <rs type="topic" corresp="recYq8ReZQ3bXtQu4"
                    >bomber counting rule</rs> agreed at <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>, and that the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recYq8ReZQ3bXtQu4">bomber counting rule</rs> would apply to the 3600
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> as well. We did not
                get very far on the 4800 <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs>
                although, under persistent questioning from <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T"
                    >Ron</persName>, <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> further
                acknowledged that at least in theory there was a figure between 6000 and 4800 which
                would not require the Soviets to “restructure” their forces, i.e., might be
                acceptable as a <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> on <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss>. The Soviets said they would consider a
                no-increase commitment on <rs type="topic" corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    >throwweight</rs> along with a unilateral commitment to reduce <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF">throwweight</rs> by 50%. They did not move on the
                length of the reduction period, although <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp"
                    >Karpov</persName> suggested that the 7-year period we want would be acceptable
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">if</hi> we accepted their proposal for a 10-year
                period of <rs corresp="recMjLDCnI9cLa32M" type="topic">compliance</rs> with the
                    <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>.</p>
            <p>We clarified somewhat the <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense &amp;
                    Space</rs> proposals <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc"
                    >Shevardnadze</persName> made to you. On the list proposal, <persName
                    corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> several times stated that if a
                space device fit within the thresholds, the Soviets would not question its purpose;
                if the device exceeded the thresholds, it could be <pb facs="0933" n="906"
                    xml:id="pg_906"/> tested only in the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recOzoeUb5OaUz29X">laboratory</rs>. This is a change from their current
                position in <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>, where they
                have argued that <hi rendition="simple_italic">any</hi>
                <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> device would be inconsistent with the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>. (We are
                having the Soviet list translated—our impression is that at least some of the
                thresholds have gone up substantially from the list the Soviets tabled in <rs
                    type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>, and thus might be in the
                ballpark.)</p>
            <p>The situation is less clear on their proposal for a 10-year commitment to <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">non-withdrawal</rs> from the
                    <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>. <persName
                    corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> described the regime that would
                apply during this period as the “narrow interpretation” or the “original
                interpretation” of the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9"
                    >Treaty</rs>. We pointed out repeatedly that there is no agreement between the
                sides about these. <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> confirmed
                that if either party committed a “gross violation” of the <rs
                    type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>, the other
                would be freed of its <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> obligations. <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> said
                the Soviets would want the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> to continue
                after the 10 years but would be ready to negotiate on what followed the period.</p>
            <p>On the whole, it was a more cordial session than we have had with <persName
                    corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> in the past. We agreed to
                reconvene the <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                </gloss> experts meeting today after the morning plenary. <persName
                    corresp="recJYLsVHtwd9Q6nh">Ken</persName> will discuss <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15">nuclear testing</rs>. We do
                not plan to suggest a <gloss target="#t_CW_1">
                    <rs corresp="rectadvRz4QZmc1z7" type="topic">CW</rs>
                </gloss> working group but should be prepared to have one if the Soviets want a
                meeting.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
